  "prompt": "What is Precision-Recall (PR) curve?",
  "response": "A Precision-Recall (PR) curve is a graphical representation used to evaluate the performance of binary classification models. It illustrates the trade-off between precision and recall for different threshold settings.\n\n- **Precision (Positive Predictive Value)** is the ratio of true positive results to the total number of positive results (both true positives and false positives) predicted by the model. It indicates how many of the predicted positive instances are truly positive.\n\n- **Recall (Sensitivity or True Positive Rate)** is the ratio of true positive results to the total number of actual positive instances. It measures the model's ability to correctly identify all relevant instances.\n\nThe PR curve plots precision on the y-axis and recall on the x-axis for varying threshold values used to classify observations as positive. In general, a higher area under the curve (AUC) of the PR curve indicates a better performing model.\n\nPR curves are particularly useful when dealing with imbalanced datasets where the positive class is rare. Unlike the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve, which considers the true positive rate versus the false positive rate, the PR curve focuses on the performance regarding the positive class, making it more informative in such cases. \n\nKey points about the PR curve:\n- A model that performs well will have a curve that is close to the top-right corner of the chart, indicating high precision and high recall.\n- If precision is more critical, a model should aim for a higher value of precision over recall, and vice versa if recall is more important.\n- The baseline (no-skill) precision in a PR curve is a horizontal line that represents the proportion of the positive class in the dataset.",
